## Abstract

The Humanity Score Protocol (HSP) v0.4 establishes a rigorous, multi-layer probabilistic framework for distinguishing organic human behavior from synthetic coordination on digital social graphs. By decomposing authenticity into four orthogonal signal layers—temporal behavior (Hawkes processes), linguistic diversity (topic entropy & divergence), network topology (spectral clustering & conductance), and collective synchronicity (cross-correlation tensors)—the protocol transforms synthetic detection from a heuristic classification task into a mathematically constrained inference problem. 

This thesis formalizes the **Conductance Lower Bound Theorem**, proving that large-scale, low-conductance clusters are statistically incompatible with organic human social structure under Dunbar’s cognitive constraint and small-world expansion dynamics. We further derive the **Adversarial Taxing Dilemma**, demonstrating that evading network-layer detection forces adversaries into cross-cluster interaction, which multiplicatively increases operational cost and triggers behavioral and synchronicity penalties. The protocol is hardened with surrogate null-model testing for viral event disambiguation, Zero-Knowledge audit trails for regulatory compliance, and strategic honeypot deployment for automated crawler validation. Full mathematical proofs, calibration methodologies, and implementation benchmarks are provided, positioning HSP v0.4 as a verifiable, economically deterrent framework for restoring informational integrity.

