## Chapter 4: Layer B – Temporal Behavior

### 4.1 Hawkes Process Estimation
Let $\{t_i\}_{i=1}^n$ be interaction timestamps for account $a$. The intensity is modeled as:
$$
\lambda(t) = \mu(t) + \sum_{t_i < t} \alpha \left(1 + \frac{t-t_i}{\eta}\right)^{-(1+\theta)}
$$
- $\mu(t)$: Periodic spline capturing circadian/weekly rhythms.
- $\phi(\tau)$: Power-law kernel captures human burstiness with long memory.

Parameters $(\alpha, \eta, \theta)$ estimated via Maximum Likelihood Estimation (MLE) using the `tick` library.

### 4.2 Branching Ratio & Behavioral Loss
$$
n = \int_0^\infty \phi(\tau) d\tau = \frac{\alpha \eta}{\theta}
$$
**Empirical Baseline:** Human $n \in [0.6, 0.9]$; Poisson/bot $n \approx 0$. Stationarity constraint: $n < 0.95$.
$$
\mathcal{L}_B = 1 - \tanh\left(\frac{n}{n_{\text{human}}}\right), \quad n_{\text{human}} = 0.7
$$

### 4.3 Robustness to Jitter & Clock Obfuscation
Randomized posting delays reduce apparent burstiness but flatten $\phi(\tau)$ toward exponential decay, lowering $n$. Spectral analysis of inter-arrival time distributions distinguishes human heavy tails from bot light tails (K-S test, $p < 0.01$).

