## Chapter 9: Adversarial Robustness & Economic Deterrence

### 9.1 The Taxing Dilemma: Multi-Layer Cost Model
Let $\mathcal{C}_{\text{attack}}$ be the expected operational cost to maintain synthetic status below detection threshold. To evade Layer N, adversary must increase $\Phi(S)$. This requires routing bot traffic to external, honest nodes $H$. The cost scales as:
$$
\mathcal{C}_{\text{attack}}(\Phi) \approx c_0 \cdot \frac{1}{\Phi} + \gamma_B \mathbb{E}[\mathcal{L}_B \mid \Phi] + \gamma_C \mathbb{E}[\mathcal{L}_C \mid \Phi]
$$
where:
- $c_0/\Phi$: Proxy, rate-limit, and scheduling cost to generate cross-cluster edges.
- $\gamma_B, \gamma_C$: Penalty multipliers from exposed temporal/synchronicity filters.

As $\Phi \uparrow$, $\mathcal{C}_{\text{attack}}$ grows superlinearly because cross-cluster interaction forces bots to operate on heterogeneous human timelines, triggering $\mathcal{L}_B$ (abnormal IAT) and $\mathcal{L}_C$ (phase drift). The Nash equilibrium favors compliance over evasion.

### 9.2 Attack-Defense Matrix
| Attack Vector | Detection Mechanism | Mathematical Guarantee |
|---------------|---------------------|------------------------|
| Bursty IAT simulation | Hawkes branching ratio $n$ | $n>0.5$ requires self-excitation; exposes periodic kernel under spectral analysis |
| Randomized jitter | Surrogate $Z_\Psi$ | Jitter destroys coordination; $Z_\Psi \leq 2$ fails significance threshold |
| Fake link injection | Conductance theorem $\Phi(S)$ | $\Phi(S)<0.05$ violates weak-tie invariant; $P<10^{-9}$ for $|S|>100$ |
| Cross-cluster routing | Taxing dilemma + $\mathcal{L}_B, \mathcal{L}_C$ | Exposes to target Hawkes filters; increases $Z_\Psi$ variance |
| LLM topic mimicry | Stratified JS divergence + long-horizon variance | Synthetic variance suppression $\text{Var}(\mathcal{L}) < 0.02$ flagged |

